<HEADLINE>
<P>
PATIENCE PAYS OFF FOR POSSIBLY PERFECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Although the $212,800 Santa Barbara Handicap didn't unfold as expected, the 
result was no surprise. 
</P>
<P>
 On paper, Possibly Perfect figured to go to the front Sunday and lead her four 
rivals for the entire 1 1/4 miles on the turf. 
</P>
<P>
 However, Kent Desormeaux was content to keep the 7-10 favorite Possibly 
Perfect in second behind Waitryst for most of the way, before taking the lead 
and going on to a half-length victory over Pracer in 2:00 2/5. 
</P>
<P>
 By winning the Santa Barbara, Possibly Perfect joined Lakeway as the only 
winner of two Grade I races at the meeting. Before Sunday, she had won the 
Santa Ana on March 19. 
</P>
<P>
 Trainer Bobby Frankel hasn't seen either one of the victories by the 
4-year-old Northern Baby filly. He was in Louisiana saddling You And I in the 
Louisiana Derby last month, and Sunday he didn't come to the races after being 
at his barn in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps, the way things are going, Frankel will stay away when Possibly 
Perfect returns. 
</P>
<P>
 "Bobby told me that Desormeaux knows how to ride this filly and not to worry 
about that," assistant trainer Humberto Ascanio said. " . . . Kent rode her 
with a lot of confidence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
