NATION IN BRIEF; FLORIDA; ENGINEERS REPAIR FAULTY SHUTTLE RADAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Engineers working frantically on both sides of the Atlantic Ocean fixed a 
broken radar on the space shuttle Endeavour, and the instrument was operating 
perfectly, the Kennedy Space Center reported. The fix will allow the shuttle to 
create an unprecedented three-dimensional map of Earth's mountains, volcanoes, 
forests, deserts, oceans and rivers. After tedious testing, engineers in Europe 
and at the Johnson Space Center in Houston had traced the problem to a bad 
sensor in a low-voltage safety circuit inside the high-power amplifier for one 
of the radars. 
</P>
