<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; NATIONWIDE; BLACKS' LUNG CANCER SUSCEPTIBILITY CITED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Blacks may be biologically more likely than whites to develop lung cancer from 
smoking, according to a study released at a cancer conference in San Francisco. 
The results are particularly relevant because cigarette manufacturers have been 
accused of aggressively targeting blacks in their marketing campaigns, said 
John Richie of the American Health Foundation, which conducted the study. "Our 
initial data seem to indicate that blacks have a poorer capacity than whites to 
detoxify NNK, one of the most important tobacco-related carcinogens linked to 
lung cancer," Richie told a meeting of the American Assn. for Cancer Research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
