<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: BUENA PARK; LIBRARY DISTRICT OK AS IS, STUDY FINDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By sDEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A consultant has recommended that the Buena Park Library District remain 
independent after concluding that a merger with either the city or the county 
would not save a significant amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
 If the library were merged with the city, the consultant said, only minimal 
cost savings would result and it would not generate new revenue. 
</P>
<P>
 The consultant also reported that consolidating with the county's public 
library system would not "improve the library district's short- or long-term 
financial prospects." 
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, the study, prepared by BSI Consultants Inc. of San Diego, 
found that current library revenue is not sufficient to cover expected spending 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
 The report recommended that the library district find ways to generate 
additional revenue so it could maintain its current level of service. 
</P>
<P>
 In previous years, budget shortfalls have been offset by spending the surplus 
from the previous year's budget, said library director Colleen McGregor. 
</P>
<P>
 But the study found that in three years, the library will not have a surplus 
sufficient to continue covering state revenue losses. 
</P>
<P>
 The library district, founded in 1919, receives 85% of its funding from 
property taxes. 
</P>
<P>
 But in the past two years, the library has faced declining revenue due to 
state property tax shifts, forcing the library to cut back some services. 
</P>
<P>
 Trustees were expected to discuss the report at last week's meeting, but the 
session was postponed to May 4 because the consultant was unable to attend. 
</P>
<P>
 The board in September hired the consultant for $10,000, with the funds 
provided by the nonprofit Friends of the Library. 
</P>
<P>
 Trustee Robert Niccum said that "it's certainly good news to read in the 
report that the current way the district is organized as a special district is 
the best way at the current time to be providing services to the community." 
</P>
<P>
 But Niccum added that because of continued revenue losses, he is concerned 
about the district's ability to maintain services at the present level. sDEBRA 
CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
